         <p>
<hi rend="bold">Advent Sunday. December 2</hi><hi rend="bold superscript underline">nd</hi><hi rend="bold">, 1906.</hi>
         </p>
         <p>A cold grey day. <persName xml:id="55">Knox</persName> celebrated at 8 a.m. when there were 43 communicants. At Mattins there was but a small congregation. I preached on "Christ &amp; the Temple&#8211;market", combining in my text S. Matt. XXI. 12, 13, and I. Cor. iii. 16, 17. I celebrated after Mattins, when there were 83 comm<hi rend="superscript underline">ts</hi>.</p>
         <p>In the afternoon I walked with <persName xml:id="113">Harold</persName> to S<hi rend="superscript underline">t</hi> Anne's S. Lambeth, and preached to a little congregation of about 25 of very respectably&#8211;dressed men.  On my return to the Rectory I found the commissariat&#8211;department in confusion, the hot&#8211;water apparatus having gone wrong.</p>
         <p>There was a fair congregation at Evensong, when I preached on "Idolatry". We sang the 'Dies Irae' on our knees after the Blessing.</p>
         <p>Knox and <persName xml:id="1180" display="no">his wife</persName> came in to supper.</p>
         <p><persName xml:id="1292" display="no">M<hi rend="superscript underline">r</hi> Andrew Bell</persName>, the Secretary of the Glasgow United Y.M.C.A., came to see me, &amp; extracted a promise that I would attend the annual meeting in October 1907. </p>
         <p>
<hi rend="bold">[152]</hi>
         </p>
